  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Targeted Legal and Psychosocial Assistance for Young Refugees in Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Whilst the conflict in Uganda has come to an end, the country is refuge to at least 200,000 people from the Great Lakes region, Somalia as well as Southern Sudan. These refugees are vulnerable to harassment, detention, torture, exploitation and deportation back to conflict zones. This is made worse by language barriers and a lack of sympathy from the local population and local authorities. The project aims to help several thousand refugees. They will prioritise children, people who have suffered violence, torture or risk of deportation; people with disabilities, or those living with HIV/AIDS; and those who are abused and discriminated against because of their sexual orientation. The result will be that around 10,000 refugees will get legal aid, counselling services and English language classes all of which will help them gain greater security and protection in Uganda. Government staff such as the police and magistrates will have been trained in refugee rights which will result in a more sympathetic response to their plight.</narrative>
  </description>
